<subSubSection pageId="213" pageNumber="818" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="213.[172,1380,254,835]" pageId="213" pageNumber="818">dense, and short. Finely scaled tail is ¢.119% of head-body length. Incisors are white; molars are small and narrow.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="213" pageNumber="818" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="213.[172,1380,254,835]" pageId="213" pageNumber="818">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[174,285,365,399]" pageId="213" pageNumber="818">Habitat.</emphasis>
Lowland and montane forests at elevations of 915-2310 m. In a recent survey in Sinharaja forest area, Ohia Rats were trapped in pristine closed forests, with relatively dense canopy and sparse undergrowth and in secondary forest selectively logged in the 1970s. They were not caught in abandoned villages or plantations.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
